=== Theoretical ===

==== Kinetic theory ====
The ideal gas law can also be derived from first principles using the kinetic theory of gases, in which several simplifying assumptions are made, chief among which are that the molecules, or atoms, of the gas are point masses, possessing mass but no significant volume, and undergo only elastic collisions with each other and the sides of the container in which both linear momentum and kinetic energy are conserved.

First we show that the fundamental assumptions of the kinetic theory of gases imply that
: formula_59

Consider a container in the formula_60 Cartesian coordinate system. For simplicity, we assume that a third of the molecules moves parallel to the formula_61-axis, a third moves parallel to the formula_62-axis and a third moves parallel to the formula_63-axis. If all molecules move with the same velocity formula_64, denote the corresponding pressure by formula_65. We choose an area formula_66 on a wall of the container, perpendicular to the formula_61-axis. When time formula_68 elapses, all molecules in the volume formula_69 moving in the positive direction of the formula_61-axis will hit the area. There are formula_71 molecules in a part of volume formula_69 of the container, but only one sixth (i.e. a half of a third) of them moves in the positive direction of the formula_61-axis. Therefore, the number of molecules formula_74 that will hit the area formula_66 when the time formula_68 elapses is formula_77.

When a molecule bounces off the wall of the container, it changes its momentum formula_78 to formula_79. Hence the magnitude of change of the momentum of one molecule is formula_80. The magnitude of the change of momentum of all molecules that bounce off the area formula_66 when time formula_68 elapses is then formula_83. From formula_84 and formula_85 we get

: formula_86

We considered a situation where all molecules move with the same velocity formula_64. Now we consider a situation where they can move with different velocities, so we apply an &quot;averaging transformation&quot; to the above equation, effectively replacing formula_65 by a new pressure formula_33 and formula_90 by the arithmetic mean of all squares of all velocities of the molecules, i.e. by formula_91 Therefore
: formula_92
which gives the desired formula.

Using the Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution, the fraction of molecules that have a speed in the range formula_64 to formula_94 is formula_95, where
: formula_96
and formula_36 denotes the Boltzmann constant. The root-mean-square speed can be calculated by
: formula_98

Using the integration formula
